Network indices of the Florentine families weddings network

We shall compute several indices of the Florentine families weddings network. We shall use the igraph package, and the networks adjacency matrix flo that comes with the network package. Therefore we start by attaching both packages (which I have already installed) and loading the data:

library(network)
library(igraph)
library(printr)   #to display matrices and tables nicely
data(flo)

Lets check the matrix:

Now we define a graph from this adjacency matrix

FLO=graph_from_adjacency_matrix(flo,mode="undirected")
plot(FLO)

#To improve the representation, see the available parameters in help(igraph.plotting)

It has two connected components, as we can confirm with:

components(FLO)$no
## [1] 2
components(FLO)$csize
## [1] 15  1
groups(components(FLO))
## $`1`
##  [1] "Acciaiuoli"   "Albizzi"      "Barbadori"    "Bischeri"    
##  [5] "Castellani"   "Ginori"       "Guadagni"     "Lamberteschi"
##  [9] "Medici"       "Pazzi"        "Peruzzi"      "Ridolfi"     
## [13] "Salviati"     "Strozzi"      "Tornabuoni"  
## 
## $`2`
## [1] "Pucci"

From now on, we shall restrict ourselves to the giant component, excluding the Pucci. We can do it in two ways: removing the corresponding node (with delete_vertices) or taking the subgraph induced by the nodes in the giant component (with induced_subgraph):

Removing the Pucci:

FLOp=delete_vertices(FLO,"Pucci")
plot(FLOp)

Taking the subgraph:

FLOpp=induced_subgraph(FLO,v=groups(components(FLO))[[1]])
plot(FLOpp)

Both graphs are the same:

is_isomorphic_to(FLOp,FLOpp)
## [1] TRUE

We shall work from now on with FLOp. Lets compute its vectors of nodes and edges, its order, its size, and its adjacency matrix:

Indices related to degrees

Its density is:

round(edge_density(FLOp),4)
## [1] 0.1905

Let us now compute its degree distribution and some of its moments. The degrees of the nodes:

degree(FLOp)
##   Acciaiuoli      Albizzi    Barbadori     Bischeri   Castellani 
##            1            3            2            3            3 
##       Ginori     Guadagni Lamberteschi       Medici        Pazzi 
##            1            4            1            6            1 
##      Peruzzi      Ridolfi     Salviati      Strozzi   Tornabuoni 
##            3            3            2            4            3

Its range

range(degree(FLOp))
## [1] 1 6

The average degree

round(mean(degree(FLOp)),4)
## [1] 2.6667

that should be equal to

round((n-1)*edge_density(FLOp),4)
## [1] 2.6667

The degrees (sample) variance

round(var(degree(FLOp)),4)
## [1] 1.9524

The degrees distribution function:

round(degree_distribution(FLOp),4)
## [1] 0.0000 0.2667 0.1333 0.4000 0.1333 0.0000 0.0667

The degrees (cumulative) distribution function:

degree_distribution(FLOp,cumulative=TRUE)  #Beware! This is P(degree>=k)
## [1] 1.00000000 1.00000000 0.73333333 0.60000000 0.20000000 0.06666667
## [7] 0.06666667
TrDD=c(1-degree_distribution(FLOp,cumulative=TRUE)[-1],1)
round(TrDD,4)
## [1] 0.0000 0.2667 0.4000 0.8000 0.9333 0.9333 1.0000

Their graphs:

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot(0:max(degree(FLOp)), degree_distribution(FLOp),pch=20,main="Degree density",xlab="Degree",ylab="Probability",type="o")
plot(0:max(degree(FLOp)), TrDD,pch=20,main="Degree cumulative distribution",xlab="Degree",ylab="Probability",type="o")

The neighborhood of a node is computed with neighbors

neighbors(FLOp,v="Medici")
## + 6/15 vertices, named:
## [1] Acciaiuoli Albizzi    Barbadori  Ridolfi    Salviati   Tornabuoni
plot(induced_subgraph(FLOp,v=as.vector(neighbors(FLOp,v="Medici"))))

The degree assortativity can be computed with assortativity_degree:

round(assortativity_degree(FLOp),4)
## [1] -0.3748

The coreness of each node can be computed with coreness

coreness(FLOp)
##   Acciaiuoli      Albizzi    Barbadori     Bischeri   Castellani

plot(FLOp,vertex.color=coreness(FLOp))

The h-neighborhoods can be computed with the function ego and parameter order set to h

ego(FLOp,order=2,nodes="Medici")
## [[1]]
## + 12/15 vertices, named:
##  [1] Medici     Acciaiuoli Albizzi    Barbadori  Ridolfi    Salviati  
##  [7] Tornabuoni Ginori     Guadagni   Castellani Strozzi    Pazzi

To compute the relative hop plot function we can do the following:

rel.hop.plot=function(G){
F=function(x){length(unlist(ego(G,order=x,nodes=V(G))))/length(V(G))^2}
sapply(1:diameter(G),FUN=F)}
plot(rel.hop.plot(FLOp),pch=20,main="Relative hop plot",xlab="Hops",ylab="Probability",type="o")

Indices related to clustering and transitivity

The main function to compute clustering coefficients is transitivity: with type=local it gives the clustering coefficient of nodes; with type=average, the average clustering coefficient; and with type=global, the transitivity.

The clustering coefficient of the Medici:

round(transitivity(FLOp, type="local",vids="Medici"),4)
## [1] 0.0667

The vector of clustering coefficients:

TR=matrix(transitivity(FLOp, type="local"),nrow=1,byrow=TRUE)
dimnames(TR)[2]=list(VF)
round(TR,4)
Acciaiuoli Albizzi Barbadori Bischeri Castellani Ginori Guadagni Lamberteschi Medici Pazzi Peruzzi Ridolfi Salviati Strozzi Tornabuoni
NaN 0 0 0.3333 0.3333 NaN 0 NaN 0.0667 NaN 0.6667 0.3333 0 0.3333 0.3333

The average clustering coefficient:

round(transitivity(FLOp, type="average"),4)  #Not taking into account degree 1 nodes
## [1] 0.2182
round(transitivity(FLOp, type="average",isolates="zero"),4)  #Setting c(v)=0 for degree 1 nodes
## [1] 0.16

The transitivity:

round(transitivity(FLOp),4)
## [1] 0.1915

As far a the edges support, we can compute it as follows. First, compute the triangles in the graph

tr=triangles(FLOp)
tr
## + 9/15 vertices, named:
## [1] Medici     Ridolfi    Tornabuoni Strozzi    Bischeri   Peruzzi   
## [7] Strozzi    Castellani Peruzzi

And now we can obtain the list of edges in triangles, with multiplicities. Its frequency table will be the support of each supported edge

edg.tr=function(x){E(FLOp,path=c(x,x[1]))}
edges=tapply(tr,rep(1:(length(tr)/3),each = 3),FUN=edg.tr)
EF[unlist(edges)]
## [1] "Medici|Ridolfi"     "Ridolfi|Tornabuoni" "Medici|Tornabuoni" 
## [4] "Bischeri|Strozzi"   "Bischeri|Peruzzi"   "Peruzzi|Strozzi"   
## [7] "Castellani|Strozzi" "Castellani|Peruzzi" "Peruzzi|Strozzi"
Supps=table(EF[unlist(edges)])
Supps
Bischeri|Peruzzi Bischeri|Strozzi Castellani|Peruzzi Castellani|Strozzi Medici|Ridolfi Medici|Tornabuoni Peruzzi|Strozzi Ridolfi|Tornabuoni
1 1 1 1 1 1 2 1

Finally, the average support coefficient can be computed by means of

round(length(tr)/m,4)
## [1] 0.45
